  p All shapes and figures on this site were created by Victor Stok from Driebergen, Netherlands.
  p Additionally he analysed "Rubik's Snake" mathematically. Due to that interesting results and an incredibly diverse collection emerged.
  
  p Thanks, Victor!

  p The following shapes are subdivided into three main categories:
  ol
    li 2D-shapes ("in one plane")
    li 3D-shapes ("spacious")
    li convex shapes

  p The 2D-shapes are classified into the number of embedded squares (edge length = longest side of triangle), that either contain no hole or up to 6 inner square holes max. Victor holds that he found out about every 2D-shape there is, in which the "Rubik's Snake" is completely self-contained.

  p The 3D-shapes contain a number of extraordinarily fine and symmetrical figures.

  p Convex shapes are characterized as follows: You can reach any spot from any spot of the shape (in the interior or on the surface) with a linking line, that exclusively runs in the interior or on the surface of the shape. Victor again holds that he found out about every convex shape there is. There are (only!) three of those shapes to be exact - two in 2D and one in 3D - no more! Victor's challenge to all people are interested: It exist only the described 2D- and convex figures ... "I want to challenge people to prove I am wrong. If they can find more 2D solutions or convex figures, send them in!"

  p Victor is using for the notation of the 2D-figures a description of the 23 possible twists, see below.

