  h2 Notation of 2D-figures, written by Victor:

  p In the 2D world there are two ways for a piece to twist: either it is straight or it twists by 90 degrees.
  p I decided to call a straight piece 0 (zero), a piece twisted by 90 degrees, 2 (two).
  p Consequently, the figure 
  img(src='img/Victor_2D.jpg')#Victor_2D.jpg
  p is called: 00200022000200022000200

  p As one can see only the twists, not the pieces, are described. Therefore there are 23 digits above.
  p It is a long line so I decided to make groups of five with an open space in between. So the figure is written: 00200 02200 02000 22000 200

  p In a 2D world there are theoretically 8388608 figures possible - 23 twist which can be a 0 or a 2, therefore:
  p 2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2x2= 8388608

  p How can we exclude all impossible twists and count the exact number of possible figures? Because a figure starting with 222 is not possible.

  p Note: Why did I choose to use the numbers 0 and 2? If we want to use this description in a 3D world, we could use 1 for a twist of 45 degrees clockwise and 1' for a twist of 45 degrees counterclockwise.

  p Remark by Thomas: I use the numbers (0) 1, 2 and 3 for the four possible positions of a prisma. The angles are (0°) 90°, 180° and 270°for the twists. Because prismas are twisted four times to get it to its original position (360° twist in summary).

